messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
Um, all your doctors? Because my mom's on the floor, we think, and I can't wake her up.
How old is your mommy?
Um, I don't know, but she's not waking up.
I always try to wake her up and the baby is crying.
I was crying my head off.
Okay, can you do me a favor, sweetie? Is your mom on her stomach or her back?
I don't know.
When you look at your mommy, is she laying on her stomach?
No, she's laying on her side.
Okay, can you roll her flat on her back? Can you push her over?
No, she's too big. But are you a doctor?
No, but honey, I am going to get someone out to you. I want you to stay on the phone with me.
How long has your mommy been sleeping?
I don't know. She just stayed like this. I was trying to get her up and the baby is crying. I don't know how to make... um... I tried calling somebody, but they didn't answer.
Okay. So she's been like that for a couple of hours?
Yeah.
Is that your baby brother or sister?
Yeah. I can't make him a bottle. I don't know how.
Okay, you can't make him a bottle. How old is your brother or sister?
Oh, my sister's not here. She's at my dad's and the baby is two weeks old.
The baby is two weeks old?
Yeah.
Okay, sweetie. What's the bottle look like? Do you know where the bottles are?
I know where one bottle is, but can you really hear me? The baby's crying.
I can hear you, sweetie. I can hear you really good. You're doing a great job. Does your baby brother take a baby bottle or a pacifier?
We have cereal for him and I was trying to make the cereal, but I don't know how. The box is not open.
Okay, okay, you're doing great. Is your baby brother in a little sling, or is he laying in a crib?
No, he's in his little chair.
In his little chair? Is it a bouncy chair?
Yes, but I was trying to wake her up. I'm so tired. I'm afraid we stayed up all night.
Oh, honey, you're not going to stay up all night. We're going to get someone to help you. You're being so brave right now. I'm so proud of you. How old are you?
Five.
Five. You are doing great. What's your name?
Austin.
Austin, you are being a great helper. Do you like your new baby brother?
Yes.
What's his name?
Um, his name is Aiden.
Baby Aiden?
Yeah.
Can you show me what the bottle looks like because your mom's not waking up somehow?
Okay, that's fine. You can take the phone with you. Tell me what the bottle looks like.
It has stuff in it, but it has the stuff in it. It has the formula, and I was shaking it, but somehow the lid didn't close.
Is there water in the bottle with the formula?
Yeah, you have to put it in. That's how you make it.
You are very smart. That is how we make bottles. Did you twist the top on all the way?
Yeah, but when I was shaking it, it didn't mix.
It's okay. Sometimes it takes a little longer. If it's twisted on right, with the little eating part you suck out of, we can shake it again together. We'll shake together.
Okay.
Are you shaking it now?
No, I don't have it right now.
Can you take the phone with you? We want to try and help baby Aiden.
This is a house phone, but I can't bring the whole phone.
Okay, okay, can you set the phone down and go get the bottle and come back?
Okay.
Okay, I'm back.
Okay, I'm still here, honey. Did you get the bottle?
Yeah, I have it.
Okay, does it look more like formula now?
No, there's still formula at the bottom.
Okay, well let's shake it really hard.
I'm shaking it.
You are doing good. Sometimes the formula likes to get stuck.
I was watching a movie and I told her to get up and she didn't. She's done this two or three times already.
You're doing so good. I'm so proud of you. I'm sure your mommy is proud of you too for being such a good help.
I'm trying to wake her up. She's not waking up.
Okay. If you put your hand in front of her nose or her mouth, can you feel any breath?
Okay, I'll do that. Hold on.
I don't know because there's a new phone and I don't know if she's breathing.
Okay. Does she have any red stuff by her body?
No.
No blood? Do you know what blood looks like?
I know it's red.
Okay. You don't see any of that?
No.
Okay. All right. Well, we're doing good. How's that bottle looking?
It still has formula at the bottom. I'll try to shake it when you come because I'm trying to make him one and it's not working.
Okay, that's all right. If we shake it up, does it have enough liquid so he can get some milk maybe?
I think my mom put too much and that's why it's not working, I think.
Oh, okay. Well, can we just try and dump a little bit out so we can give him a little bit?
Hold on. Set the phone down.
It's probably the paramedics. Set the phone down and get the door. Do you see fire trucks?
Okay. My mom's laying on the floor.
They're in the kitchen now.
No, I'm just scared because the door is right there.
My phone is ringing. My phone is ringing.
Okay. Hey, Austin?
Yeah.
Help is on the way, okay? They're going to help you.
Say hi.
Okay.
Hello. They're here.
Is there someone with you? Can you show them the bottle? Maybe they can make it for your brother?
Yeah, he is right now. He's making the bottle.
Okay. All right. They're going to help you, okay?
Okay.
All right. Bye.
Bye.
